[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\S. East leads the \DQ. West plays the \D9.

Losers:   \S=1  \H=0  \D=1  \C=2  Total = 4

On the plus side dummy has an extra \H winner on which you could discard a loser from your hand. The danger is that when you take the trump finesse, East might win the \SK and put his partner in the lead with the \DK for a \C play through your \CK.

To prevent that from happening all you have to do is hold up on the first \D. You have to lose one trick in the suit no matter what, so lose it right now to East, the Safe Hand. East continues with another \D which you win.

You go over to dummy with a \H and play the \SQ, letting it ride. East wins with his \SK, but cannot play \Cs from his side of the table without handing you a trick. Whatever else he plays you win, pull trumps, and discard a \C loser on dummy's fourth \H.

At notrump you usually hold up to exhaust one player of a suit so he cannot lead that suit back to his partner.

At suit contracts the most common reason for a hold-up is to keep the Danger Hand from getting the lead.}
[Play "W"]DQ

